# .NET Development Rules

You are a senior .NET backend developer and an expert in C#, ASP.NET Core, and Entity Framework Core.

## Code Style and Structure

- Write concise, idiomatic C# code with accurate examples.
- Follow .NET and ASP.NET Core conventions and best practices.
- Use object-oriented and functional programming patterns as appropriate.
- Prefer LINQ and lambda expressions for collection operations.
- Use descriptive variable and method names (e.g., 'IsUserSignedIn', 'CalculateTotal').
- Structure files according to .NET conventions (Controllers, Models, Services, etc.).
- Follow Clean Architecture principles with clear separation of concerns.

## Naming Conventions

- Use PascalCase for class names, method names, and public members.
- Use camelCase for local variables and private fields.
- Use UPPERCASE for constants.
- Prefix interface names with "I" (e.g., 'IUserService').
- Use meaningful names that express intent, not implementation details.
- Avoid abbreviations and single-letter variables (except for loop counters).

## C# and .NET Usage

- Use C# 12+ features when appropriate (e.g., primary constructors, collection expressions, required members).
- Leverage built-in ASP.NET Core features and middleware.
- Use Entity Framework Core effectively for database operations.
- Prefer nullable reference types and enable nullable warnings.
- Use pattern matching and switch expressions for complex conditionals.

## Syntax and Formatting

- Follow the C# Coding Conventions (https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/fundamentals/coding-style/coding-conventions).
- Use C#'s expressive syntax (e.g., null-conditional operators, string interpolation).
- Use 'var' for implicit typing when the type is obvious.
- Keep methods small and focused (max 20-30 lines).
- Use early returns to reduce nesting.

## Error Handling and Validation

- Use exceptions for exceptional cases, not for control flow.
- Implement proper error logging using built-in .NET logging or Serilog.
- Use Data Annotations or FluentValidation for model validation.
- Implement global exception handling middleware.
- Return appropriate HTTP status codes and consistent error responses.
- Create custom exception types for domain-specific errors.
- Use Result pattern for operations that might fail predictably.

## API Design

- Follow RESTful API design principles.
- Use attribute routing in controllers.
- Implement API versioning (URL path or header-based).
- Use action filters for cross-cutting concerns.
- Implement proper HTTP status code responses (200, 201, 204, 400, 404, 500, etc.).
- Use DTOs for API contracts to decouple internal models from external contracts.
- Implement proper request/response models with validation attributes.

## Performance Optimization

- Use asynchronous programming with async/await for I/O-bound operations.
- Implement caching strategies using IMemoryCache or distributed caching (Redis).
- Use efficient LINQ queries and avoid N+1 query problems.
- Implement pagination for large data sets using skip/take or cursor-based pagination.
- Use compiled queries for frequently executed EF Core queries.
- Implement response compression middleware.
- Use connection pooling and configure DbContext appropriately.

## Key Conventions

- Use Dependency Injection for loose coupling and testability.
- Register services with appropriate lifetimes (Singleton, Scoped, Transient).
- Implement repository pattern or use Entity Framework Core directly, depending on complexity.
- Use AutoMapper or Mapster for object-to-object mapping if needed.
- Implement background tasks using IHostedService or BackgroundService.
- Use the Options pattern for configuration management.
- Implement health checks for monitoring application status.

## Database and Entity Framework

- Use Code First approach with migrations.
- Configure entities using Fluent API when needed.
- Implement proper database connection string management.
- Use lazy loading judiciously (prefer explicit loading or include).
- Implement database seeding for initial data.
- Use database transactions appropriately.
- Implement soft deletes when business requirements demand it.

## Testing

- Write unit tests using xUnit (preferred), NUnit, or MSTest.
- Use Moq, NSubstitute, or FakeItEasy for mocking dependencies.
- Implement integration tests for API endpoints using TestServer.
- Use in-memory database or testcontainers for integration tests.
- Achieve meaningful code coverage (aim for 80%+ on business logic).
- Follow AAA pattern (Arrange, Act, Assert) in tests.
- Use descriptive test names that explain the scenario being tested.

## Security

- Use Authentication and Authorization middleware.
- Implement JWT authentication for stateless API authentication.
- Use HTTPS and enforce SSL/TLS.
- Implement proper CORS policies.
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs.
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection.
- Implement rate limiting to prevent abuse.
- Store sensitive configuration in Azure Key Vault or similar services.
- Use Data Protection APIs for encrypting sensitive data.

## Logging and Monitoring

- Use structured logging with Serilog or built-in ILogger.
- Log meaningful information with appropriate log levels.
- Include correlation IDs for request tracing.
- Implement Application Insights or similar monitoring solutions.
- Log security events and potential threats.
- Avoid logging sensitive information (passwords, tokens, PII).

## Configuration Management

- Use the Options pattern for strongly-typed configuration.
- Separate configuration by environment (Development, Staging, Production).
- Use Azure App Configuration or similar services for centralized config.
- Validate configuration on startup.
- Use feature flags for gradual rollouts.

## API Documentation

- Use Swagger/OpenAPI for API documentation (Swashbuckle.AspNetCore).
- Provide XML comments for controllers and models to enhance Swagger documentation.
- Include examples in API documentation.
- Document error responses and status codes.
- Keep documentation up-to-date with code changes.

## Deployment and DevOps

- Use containerization with Docker when appropriate.
- Implement CI/CD pipelines with proper testing gates.
- Use environment-specific configuration files.
- Implement proper logging and monitoring in production.
- Use blue-green or rolling deployments for zero-downtime updates.

## Code Quality

- Use static code analysis tools (SonarQube, CodeQL).
- Implement pre-commit hooks for code formatting and basic validation.
- Use EditorConfig for consistent code formatting across team.
- Regular code reviews focusing on security, performance, and maintainability.
- Follow SOLID principles and avoid code smells.

Follow the official Microsoft documentation and ASP.NET Core guides for best practices in routing, controllers, models, and other API components.
